**FAQ 10: Should Paid Search Segment OP2 Goals?**
While Brand and Nonbrand benchmarks provide useful insight into demand trends, Paid Search is accountable to a single objective: driving business impact through efficient acquisition of customers. Brand queries consistently deliver the highest profitability and have been validated as incremental through MIE modeling, so as Brand interest increases, we ensure visibility across audiences to capture the opportunity. This Brand performance then supports overall channel efficiency and enables sustained investment in Nonbrand. Setting a separate Nonbrand target can constrain Brand capture and reduce total profit. Performance is best measured holistically (as aligned with AWS measurement), with flexibility to allocate spend dynamically toward the greatest impact. 

While OP2 goal granularity (Brand vs Nonbrand, and individual EU countries) provides useful planning guidance, the Paid Search team operates with a mental model centered on maximizing overall business impact through efficient customer acquisition. Brand queries consistently deliver the highest profitability and have been validated as incremental through MIE modeling; as Brand demand increases, we prioritize maximizing visibility to capture that opportunity. This performance underpins overall channel efficiency and enables sustained investment in Nonbrand. Similarly, while OP2 establishes country-level targets across EU5, investment decisions prioritize total EU regional acquisition impact rather than deploying budget into less efficient markets to meet individual country utilization targets. Given the dynamic nature of search demand, the team will shift out of headwinds to lean into tailwinds, which can create variance in segment-level performance. Ultimately, performance is measured holistically, with flexibility to allocate spend toward the highest-return opportunities - consistent with Central (AME) Paid Search’s approach of investing based on efficiency. 

